    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-02-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-02-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="331"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d331">
                <head>331. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d331fn1"
                        >Source: Department of State, Central Files, POL 27 LAOS. Secret; Exdis.
                        Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_BCE1">Bohlen</persName> and approved in S
                        on February 19. The source text is Part II of VI.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1968-02-15">February 15,
                            1968</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Laos</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>The Secretary</item>
                    <item>Deputy Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_BCE1">Charles E.
                            Bohlen</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Soviet Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DAF1">Anatoliy Dobrynin</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>During an hour and a half’s luncheon conversation the following point was touched
                    on:</p>
                <p>The Secretary said that our recent information showed that there were North
                    Vietnamese battalions around the town of Saravane in southern Laos and that if,
                    as was possible, the North Vietnamese launched an attack on the city, the U.S.
                    would become militarily involved. <persName corresp="#p_DAF1"
                        >Dobrynin</persName> made a note of the name Saravane, obviously for the
                    purpose of informing Moscow. The Secretary said that he thought the U.K. and the
                    Soviet Union as co-chairmen of the 1962 Laos arrangement had certain duties,
                    pointing out to <persName corresp="#p_DAF1">Dobrynin</persName> that this
                    agreement had been made quite independently of events in Viet-Nam. <persName
                        corresp="#p_DAF1">Dobrynin</persName> agreed.</p>
            </div>
